<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-introduction-to-matrices" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Introduction to Matrices</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.7 Matrices I
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                            <ul>
                              <li>Identify types of matrices using rows and columns</li>
                              <li>Determine properties of a matrix from rows and columns</li>
                            </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To introduce matrices, rows, and columns through a fun puzzle.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="fun-square">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p> In groups of 2-4, copy down the following grid of numbers (called a <term>matrix</term>),
                            <me>
                                \begin{bmatrix} 
                                2 &amp; 5 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\ 
                                8 &amp; 11 &amp; 6 &amp; 7 \\ 
                                4 &amp; 7 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\ 
                                6 &amp; 9 &amp; 4 &amp; 5 
                                \end{bmatrix}
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Make sure Learners copy down the numbers in a grid, not just as a list. 
                            </p> 
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Pick any number in the matrix and draw a circle around it. Then, place a cross through all the numbers in the same <term>row</term> (those that are left and right of the circled number). For example, if you circled the 11, you would cross out the numbers 8, 6, and 7 in the same row, like so:
                            <me>
                                \begin{bmatrix} 
                                2 &amp; 5 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\ 
                                \xcancel{8} &amp; ⑪ &amp; \xcancel{6} &amp; \xcancel{7} \\ 
                                4 &amp; 7 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\ 
                                6 &amp; 9 &amp; 4 &amp; 5 
                                \end{bmatrix}
                            </me>
                            How many rows are in this matrix?
                        </p>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Make sure Learners are comfortable with the idea of a row, and make sure they do not confuse it for a column.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                You can also ask the Learners which number row they crossed out. (In our example, it is the second row).
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p> Now place a cross through and all the numbers in the same <term>column</term> (those that are above and below the circled number). Continuing the example, we would cross out 5, 7, and 9 in the same column as 11:
                            <me>
                                \begin{bmatrix} 
                                2 &amp; \xcancel{5} &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\ 
                                \xcancel{8} &amp; ⑪ &amp; \xcancel{6} &amp; \xcancel{7} \\ 
                                4 &amp; \xcancel{7} &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\ 
                                6 &amp; \xcancel{9} &amp; 4 &amp; 5 
                                \end{bmatrix}
                            </me>
                            How many columns are in this matrix?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Pick any number that isn't crossed out and repeat the process, crossing out all numbers in the same row and the same column.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Repeat until every number is either circled or crossed out. You should have 4 numbers circled.
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                One possible result is:
                                <me>
                                \begin{bmatrix} 
                                \xcancel{2} &amp; \xcancel{5} &amp; \xcancel{0} &amp; ① \\ 
                                \xcancel{8} &amp; ⑪ &amp; \xcancel{6} &amp; \xcancel{7} \\ 
                                \xcancel{4} &amp; \xcancel{7} &amp; ② &amp; \xcancel{3} \\ 
                                ⑥ &amp; \xcancel{9} &amp; \xcancel{4} &amp; \xcancel{5} 
                                \end{bmatrix}
                                </me>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Add your circled numbers together, and compare your answer with other groups. What do you notice? How did this happen!
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                In our example, we have the sum <m>1 + 11 + 2 + 6 = 20</m>. For this matrix, the sum will be <m>20</m> regardless of which 4 entries are chosen (as long as they are all in different rows and columns). 
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                This property holds because the difference between any two rows is the same for all elements (e.g. row 1 and row 2 differ by 6), as is the difference between any two columns (e.g. column 1 and column 2 differ by 3).
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Learners should hopefully be surprised with this fact, since they could choose the 4 numbers! If they are not, ask them to create their own grid of numbers, and see if it has this property<mdash/>they will find that it probably does not.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Give Learners considerable time exploring this pattern, and (after a while) guide them towards features of the matrix that might explain it, such as the differences between rows and columns.
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Can you try make your own matrix which has the same property? Try a small matrix (with 2 rows and 2 columns) first to make it easier.
                        </p>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Learners should realise that for a 2 by 2 matrix, they will need the sum of the top left and the bottom right entry to equal the sum of the top right and bottom left entry. 
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                For advanced learners, see if they can generalise this to 3 by 3 and 4 by 4 matrices, and find a general condition for when this property holds.
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

